In the late 1990s, Brodsky worked on several other music endeavors outside of Cave In.
In 1997, he joined Converge after the departure of bassist Jeff Feinburg.
He performed on the band's 1998 album When Forever Comes Crashing and was later replaced by Nate Newton.
Brodsky began his solo career with the release of his debut album Expose Your Overdubs in 1999.
In the early 2000s, Brodsky continued making solo work and releasing music with his main band Cave In.

The short-lived band released the Elvis Unreleased EP and a self-titled album through Hydra Head in 2007.

Brodsky currently lives in Brooklyn, New York and is a regular contributor to the heavy-metal comedy series Two Minutes to Late Night.
